          "body": "Isaiah 5 opens as a song. The prophet identifies himself as the friend of the bridegroom, singing on behalf of his 'well-beloved' about a vineyard. The Hebrew word *yedid* (beloved, darling) is the language of covenant affection — the same root as 'Jedidiah,' the name Nathan gave Solomon meaning 'beloved of the LORD' (2 Sam 12:25). The audience hears a pastoral lyric and relaxes. Then the tone shifts. The song moves through five acts of extraordinary care — digging, clearing stones, planting finest vines (*soreq*), building a watchtower, hewing a winepress — and arrives at a devastating anti-climax: 'He expected good grapes, but it produced only worthless ones' (*beushim*, stinking things, rotten fruit). The rhetorical genius of verses 3-4 is the invitation to judge. The vineyard owner turns to Jerusalem and Judah: 'Judge between Me and My vineyard.' By agreeing that the vinedresser's response is just, they pronounce their own sentence. Verse 7 delivers the identification with the chapter's most famous wordplay in the Hebrew: God looked for *mishpat* (justice) and found *mispach* (bloodshed); for *tsedaqah* (righteousness) and heard *tsaaqah* (a cry of distress). In four Hebrew words, the entire moral history of the covenant is summarized as a pun — and the pun is devastating."
