          "title": "The sentence — withdrawal, desolation, and drought (5:5-6)",
          "body": "The sentence God announces is not primarily military conquest — it is covenantal withdrawal. He will remove the hedge, break down the wall, and charge the clouds to rain no rain. These are not arbitrary punishments; they are the reversal of the five acts of care in verses 1-2. What the LORD built, He will dismantle. What He planted, He will abandon to briars and thorns. The hedge and wall are the protective covenantal enclosure — Psalm 80:8-12 uses the same vineyard imagery to cry out over Israel's exposure: 'Why have You broken down her walls?' The withdrawal of rain connects to the Deuteronomic covenant curses (Deut 28:23-24): the same conditions Israel was warned about if they broke faith are now being announced as the sentence. Calvin noted here that God does not punish beyond what the sin demands; the punishment matches the crime precisely — a vineyard that produced nothing is left to produce nothing. The sentence is proportional, not excessive."
